  <datafield tag="500" ind1=" " ind2=" ">
    <subfield code="a">In this letter, Mary Anne Estlin reports on the forwarding of late donations for the Boston anti-slavery fair and the failure to collect a substantial contribution in Liverpool. Microscopic slides have been prepared for the Boston fair by Mary Anne Estlin&apos;s cousin, Augustin Prichard, a surgeon and son of Dr. [James Cowles] Prichard. Mary A. Estlin rejoices that William Lloyd Garrison was able to stay longer than he first planned. Estlin said about Garrison: &quot;His speech at Newcastle must do much to remove the unfavorable impression entertained of some of his tenets...We still are obliged to fight many battles for him.&quot; Friends in Exeter are likely still to contribute to the Boston fair. &quot;It makes all the difference between zeal &amp; indifference&quot; in the towns where Frederick Douglass and William Lloyd Garrison have lectured.</subfield>
